{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655854"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18686"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10295"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26456"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInhibitory neurotransmitters play a crucial role in regulating neural activity throughout the nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks calcium channels","Increases chloride conductance","Blocks sodium channels","Increases potassium conductance","Decreases chloride conductance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of GABA involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing chloride conductance\u003C/strong\u003E through GABA-A receptors. When GABA binds to its receptor, chloride channels open, allowing chloride ions to flow into the neuron according to their electrochemical gradient. This causes hyperpolarisation of the neuron, making it less likely to generate an action potential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - While some drugs affect calcium channels, this is not the primary mechanism of GABA\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases potassium conductance\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more commonly associated with G-protein coupled receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typically associated with local anaesthetics, not GABA\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases chloride conductance\u003C/strong\u003E - This would have an excitatory rather than inhibitory effect\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe influx of negatively charged chloride ions makes the membrane potential more negative, resulting in neuronal inhibition. This mechanism is essential for preventing excessive neuronal excitation in the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system.","GABA acts by increasing chloride conductance through its receptors, causing hyperpolarisation of neurons.","Glycine is another major inhibitory neurotransmitter, particularly active in the spinal cord and brainstem."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationship